The error is because `SBI_private.key` and `EIS_ENC_UAT.cer` aren't in your `Cert` directory — you only have the two new files locally. You can't reference the existing two from disk.

Two ways to handle it:

## Option A — Pull the existing keys out first, then recreate (full control)

```bash
cd ~/Cert

# Extract the two existing keys from the live secret to disk
oc get secret eiscert -n dev-communication -o jsonpath='{.data.SBI_private\.key}' | base64 -d > SBI_private.key
oc get secret eiscert -n dev-communication -o jsonpath='{.data.EIS_ENC_UAT\.cer}' | base64 -d > EIS_ENC_UAT.cer

# Now all four files exist locally — recreate the secret
oc create secret generic eiscert \
  --from-file=SBI_private.key=./SBI_private.key \
  --from-file=EIS_ENC_UAT.cer=./EIS_ENC_UAT.cer \
  --from-file=Sbi_digi_Private.key=./Sbi_digi_Private.key \
  --from-file=Sbi_digi_PublicKey.cer=./Sbi_digi_PublicKey.cer \
  --dry-run=client -o yaml | oc apply -f - -n dev-communication
```

## Option B — Patch in just the two new keys (don't touch existing)

This adds the new keys without re-reading the old ones, so there's no risk of corrupting them:

```bash
cd ~/Cert

oc patch secret eiscert -n dev-communication --type=merge -p "{\"data\":{
  \"Sbi_digi_Private.key\":\"$(base64 -w0 Sbi_digi_Private.key)\",
  \"Sbi_digi_PublicKey.cer\":\"$(base64 -w0 Sbi_digi_PublicKey.cer)\"
}}"
```

`base64 -w0` is required — without it, line-wrapped base64 breaks the JSON. (On macOS it's `base64 -i`, but on your Linux bastion `-w0` is correct.)

**Option B is the safer choice** — it never decodes/re-encodes the existing private key, so there's zero chance of altering `SBI_private.key`.

Verify after either:

```bash
oc get secret eiscert -n dev-communication -o jsonpath='{.data}' | jq keys
```

You should see all four keys. Then clean up any extracted plaintext (`shred -u SBI_private.key` if you used Option A) since private keys shouldn't linger on the bastion.

Then roll the deployment so the new mount picks up the files:

```bash
oc rollout restart deployment/<comm-deployment-name> -n dev-communication
```
